{"cursor":"37134","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n'Disinfectants' are substances that are applied to non-living objects to destroy\nmicroorganisms that are living on the objects. www.cdc.gov/oralhealth/infectioncontrol/glossary.htm\nDisinfection does not necessarily kill all microorganisms, especially resistant\nbacterial spores; it is less effective than sterilisation, which is an extreme\nphysical and/or chemical process that kills all types of life.\nDisinfectants are different from other antimicrobial agents such as antibiotics,\nwhich destroy microorganisms within the body, and antiseptics, which destroy\nmicroorganisms on living tissue. Disinfectants are also different from biocides\nâ the latter are intended to destroy all forms of life, not just microorganisms.\nDisinfectants work by destroying the cell wall of microbes or interfering with\nthe metabolism.\n\nSanitisers are substances that simultaneously clean and\ndisinfect. [http://www.midsussex.gov.uk/page.cfm?pageID=1783 Cleaning and\ndisinfecting], (2009), [[Mid Sussex|Mid Sussex District Council]], UK.\n\nBacterial endospores are most resistant to disinfectants, but some viruses and\nbacteria also possess some tolerance.\n\nDisinfectants are frequently used in hospitals, dental surgeries, kitchens, and\nbathrooms to kill infectious organisms.\n","linknr":608,"url":"Disinfectants","recorded":1362511596,"links":55,"instances":["microbiology","medicine"],"pdf":["http://www.antimicrobialcopper.com/media/149689/pr811-chilean-subway-installs-antimicrobial-copper.pdf","http://www.antimicrobialcopper.com/media/149689/pr811-chilean-subway-installs-antimicrobial-copper.pdf","http://www.bccdc.org/downloads/pdf/epid/reports/CDManual_DisinfectntSelectnGuidelines_sep2003_nov05-03.pdf"],"categories":["Disinfectants|","Hygiene","Bactericides"],"headings":["Properties","Types","Measurements of effectiveness","Home disinfectants","References","Further reading","See also","External links"],"ima